About
An all-day destination for entertainment, afternoon tea, dining, drinking, art & culture, in the heart of Covent Garden and London's West End. In 2019, LW Theatres embarked on £60 million project to restore the historic Grade 1 listed Theatre Royal Drury Lane to its former 1812 glory. Now open all day to the public, the newly restored Theatre Royal Drury Lane, affectionately known as The Lane, is reimagined as a new destination for entertainment, food, bars, art and culture, so the iconic interiors can be enjoyed by everyone not just theatregoers. Discover more about Theatre Royal Drury Lane.
Duration: 2-3 hours

The area

Address
Neighborhood: Covent Garden
Whether you're headed here to check out the multitude of shops, theaters, cafes, pubs, and restaurants, or simply to be among the multitude of people who pass through this pretty part of town, you'll love soaking up the festive and historic atmosphere in and around Covent Garden. Even if you don't have tickets to the opera or a show at one of the many famous theaters here, don't be surprised if find yourself captivated by some impromptu act of a street performer wowing the crowds in Covent Garden's Piazza. If you do have tickets, you'll be pleased to note that many of the local eateries accommodate theatergoers with prix fixe menus, early dinners, and later than usual opening hours.

    Theatre Royal Drury Lane tour
    On a visit to London we decided to do the Theatre Royal Drury Lane tour. They go 2 a day and we picked the 10:30am tour. We were welcomed warmly and directed to a a seating area to await the start of the tour. We were lucky enough to be the only people booked on the tour, which was fantastic. The theatre has been recently renovated, to a very high standard. We were taken around by the fabulous David who told tales and provided facts. It was so interesting. We visited the Royal room and sat on the sofa that the Royal family use when they visit the theatre. We went in the auditorium, down in the tunnels under the theatre. David told us historical facts and ghost stories. The room where afternoon tea is served is lovely, next time we'll book that. I would highly recommend this as a must do if you love theatres

No ushers in sight once show started
Oct 2024 • Solo
I came here earlier this month to see Il Volo. The venue was nice. Not too big - nice and intimate. I had a really good seat in the 4th row, which was comfortable. Il Volo were wonderful. The only thing that spoiled the night for me was the lack of control from ushers. Or lack of ushers, as I didn’t actually see any once the concert had started! They were holding up cards before the concert started, banning the use of mobile phones. However, once the concert started, out came the mobile phones, which was very distracting and continued throughout the whole show, and nobody did anything. The ushers seemed to have disappeared. Also, although most of the audience were very well behaved, there were very loud Venezuelans to my left and behind me who talked and sang loudly throughout the show. Again, nothing was done. I had paid to hear Il Volo sing, not the audience members! And the ticket cost a lot of money! Add to that, I’d spent a lot of money on a train ticket from South West Wales (more than the concert ticket!), and a hotel room for the night too, only for these Venezuelans to spoil the show! Why was nothing done? Where were the others? They should have been warned, and if they continued to behave in such a manner, they should have been removed from the theatre. We all want to enjoy the show, especially given the costs involved! I’m reluctant to come back here again as I don’t want this happening again. Please could your ushers do the work they’re paid to do!
